The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Monday, December 22, 2003  Business Briefs																								 Mumbai, Dec. 21: Videsh Sanchar Nigam Ltd (VSNL) has sought regulatory approval from Trai to reduce prices on one of its premium connectivity modes, DS3, citing an increase in bandwidth on a submarine cable system. VSNL has sought a 10 to 20 per cent reduction on DS3 lines, a mode providing 45 mbps connectivity and is mainly used by BPO companies in the country.																								 New Delhi, Dec. 21: The Reserve Bank (RBI) has identified eight banks for the implementation of risk-based supervision on a pilot basis as part of efforts to mitigate risks in view of growing integration of domestic markets with external ones.																								 New Delhi, Dec. 21: The government has allowed boards of directors of unlisted companies to decide the price for making preferential allotments as well as sweat equity issue, but has capped the latter at 15 per cent of their paid-up capital or a maximum of up to Rs 5 crore.																								 Calcutta, Dec. 21: Worried over the non-availability of sufficient quality coking coal in the country, Steel Authority of India Ltd (SAIL) will source one million tonne more coking coal from abroad in the next fiscal which would take the companys total coal bill to Rs 4,000 crore.																								 New Delhi, Dec. 21: Domestic two-wheeler sales grew 9.3 per cent in April-November on the back of a higher demand for motorcycles and a resurgent scooter market. Data compiled by the Society of Indian Automobile Manufacturers showed that 3.58 million two-wheelers were sold in the first eight months this fiscal against 3.27 million units a year ago.
